{
  "texts": [
    "The following three subsections will independently elaborate on each formulaic representation, while discussing their connections and differences.",
    "Suppose we sample the initial data x 0 ∼ q(x) from a real data distribution q(x).",
    "By using the forward diffusion process to gradually add noise to the initial data x 0, a series of noisy data x 1,..., x T are obtained.",
    "According to the properties of Markov processes and the chain rule of probability, we can represent the joint distribution of all data as q(x 1,..., x T |x 0), q(x 1,..., x T |x 0) = T ∏ t=1 q(x t |x t-1).",
    "The transition kernel q(x t |x t-1) is designed manually in DDPM (Ho et al. 2020), and noise is gradually added to the initial data at each step of the transition."
  ]
}